      {
        "id": 4368164,
        "name": "Robert Alfert",
        "username": "Robert.A.Jr",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/robert.a.jr/{size}/76968_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-05-14T00:01:19.284Z",
        "cooked": "<p>This is a strikingly fantastic young wine.  It throws out the window my fascination with old vines, here we have vines of like 4-7 years.  But then again, they are massale selections from Lafleur.  So perhaps vine genetics may mean something.  Or, we have some excellent winemaking going on.  Or I\u2019m just babbling cause I fng love this little wine.  Though at $100, it ain\u2019t that little.</p>\n<p>Love the translucence to this wine, perhaps projecting that this will be a lithe beauty.  And it delivers that way.  Aromatics are wild, brambly red and dark raspberry vines meandering down to the beach of a dry riverbed.  Aromatics of crushed stones, wild flowers and spicy fruit.  The 60% Cab Franc shows on this wine, a leaner profile and tinges of green.  But it\u2019s the minerality that keeps rearing its head as I swirl.  Like someone took these river bed pebbles, put them on an anvil then pulverized them into dust.  I think the youth of the vines show on the finish, which is a bit clipped and green.  The tannins are moderate and chalky.  Overall an excellent young wine with a ton of energy.  Will be interesting to see how this wine, and subsequent vintages, evolve.</p>\n<p>Right now, 93 pts.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 10,
        "updated_at": "2024-05-14T00:04:05.818Z",
